A chief risk driver of Brent oil price are events on the International plane, especially in geographic locations that are vital to the supply of crude oil. Geopolitical instability in the middle east and government instability in oil-producing nations such as Venezuela are crucial to the supply of oil. U.S. House of Representatives approved the new sanctions targeting Russia, which, according to Elizabeth Rosenberg, “will rearrange the way the global energy industry does business with Russia and significantly increases the risk around dealings with Russia.” (https://www.platts.com/latest-news/oil/washington/us-congress-poised-to-pass-new-russia-energy-27859482) The bill prohibits U.S. companies from investing in Arctic, deepwater and shale crude projects in which Russian firms have a 33% or more stake. This comes as Venezuela may default on its loans in a PDVSA/Rosneft deal which would give Russia’s Rosneft 49.9% ownership of PDVSA’s U.S. refining subsidiary Citgo. The U.S. has sanctioned 13 Venezuelan government officials, including officials with the PDVSA. There was backlash from U.S. refiners after initial talks of sanctions involved stopping imports of Venezuelan oil (third biggest supplier to the U.S.) - the American Fuel and Petroleum Manufacturers wrote a letter warning the Trump administration about how the sanctions “would disadvantage many U.S. refineries..” (https://www.platts.com/latest-news/oil/stpetersburg/venezuela-says-us-refiners-face-difficult-situation-26777599)

A six-month effort led by Saudi Arabia and Russia to reduce the glut in global oil markets has flopped. So today, in Vienna, OPEC will try its luck again, extending output cuts, probably for another nine months. It’s unlikely to spark a big rally. Inventories may have peaked, but so has OPEC discipline: even if Iraq endorses a deal, it will probably cheat. Nigeria and Libya, both exempt from the cuts, are increasing production. And America’s shale output is surging. To push oil well above $50 a barrel, OPEC and non-OPEC suppliers would have to make more drastic cuts. Saudi Arabia has pledged to do “whatever it takes” to reduce stocks; it wants higher prices to support the forthcoming initial public offering of Aramco, the state-owned producer. It may also need to influence the futures markets so that shale producers stop hedging their output. OPEC needs crafty new tactics to beat the wily frackers
